I haven’t driven this careful since I brought my children home from the hospital. 26 photographs in the back of my car from over a decade of my life. I drove from my home to the venue in silence and memories passed through my head reminding me of all I’ve gone through during the years from start to finish… the good and the bad are there. I’m happy this show is here and ready for the public to see. I’m not trying to change the world but a smile would be great.

Thank you to everyone who came to support Shelter. Had a great turnout. Enjoy this time-lapse from the show.  Hope to do another one of these next year and thanks to @alabamacenterforarch for the venue and @williamsblackstock @cahababrewing @h2realestate for sponsoring the event. #architecture #aiabirmingham #aiaalabama #alabama

I captured this building with a 50mm and at some point you won’t be able to photograph this perspective or isolate this building as a singular object. Soon it will become part of the whole as the town grows and adjacent buildings are built honoring the ones next to it. I love these photographs because it is a record in time and it will have history associated with it. I recently bought the books on Rosemary Beach by photographer, Richard Sexton, and then the Seaside book photographed by Steven Brooke and their photographs record the essence of a town so romantically and the books serve a piece of history and a blueprint how to document a growing town. I love to look at their photographs then go back to the communities and see how its aged but still remain timeless. I feel very fortunate to photograph at Alys and I’m constantly inspired by the planning and architecture there and it is so special to be there as witness with a camera. 
.
#architecture #alysbeach #30a #design #building

I love the moment the frame is set, the tripod sturdy, the details checked, and the light is perfect and no one is around. This photo is certainly one of those moments. You stand before a beautiful space and you have an intimate experience with arcitecture. You can feel that in Phillips Exeter Academy Library, Nelson-Atkins Museum, Fort Morgan or anything with great thoughtful design no matter the limits. In this photo, I remember experiencing silence, and the light and the wonderful sunkisses on the tops of the brown pillows. I remember feeling comfortable and peaceful. I remember being able to feel the fabric on the furniture without ever having to touch it. I also wondered how in the hell people can construct something so beautiful with materials we take from the earth. The timbers, the stone, the fabric... It all grew and was formed or produced somewhere else and then it came here to be assembled together to form shelter and a delight to the eye. I’ve had quite a few of these experiences over 16 years of photography and they never get old and I’m reminded why I chose this profession and why I love design and why I love a photograph. Do yourself a favor and go to a space or sit in nature and just sit in silence and observe, and most importantly, feel and feel strongly. Maybe take a photograph. Remembering the feeling before you close the shutter and make a photograph is significant. 
.
.
